  "audience_level": "first-year university / advanced high school, completed Topics 3–5 (limits, laws, one-sided, infinity)",
  "topic_goal": "Teach the Squeeze Theorem as the standard tool when limit laws fail on oscillating or bounded-vanishing products, culminating in sin(x)/x → 1.",
  "topic_takeaways": [
    "If f ≤ g ≤ h near a and outer limits agree at L, then lim g = L.",
    "Zero-bound form |g| ≤ M with M → 0 is the everyday corollary.",
    "Product laws require each factor to have a limit, oscillation means squeeze instead.",
    "Classic results: x² cos(1/x) → 0, x sin(1/x) → 0, sin x/x → 1, sin x/x → 0 at ∞.",
    "sin(x)/x → 1 is the limit that powers derivative-of-sine later."
  ],
